<!-- PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">04 — Common Failures</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians diagnose most often in SoCal commercial freezers</h2>

    <div class="problems-grid">
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Not Holding 0°F / Temperature Rising</h3>
        <p>Refrigerant leak (slow loss over weeks, sudden loss from a fitting), dirty condenser coils preventing adequate heat rejection in SoCal's warm ambient, or a failing compressor. In a busy kitchen, the ambient temperature around the unit can be 95–105°F — and Inland Empire kitchens push past 110°F in summer. Any degraded component gets stressed faster than in a cooler environment.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Compressor Running Constantly</h3>
        <p>The unit is working against a thermal load it can't overcome. Most common causes in SoCal commercial kitchens: dirty condenser coils (the #1 reason), low refrigerant, or a door gasket that doesn't fully seal. A freezer that never cycles off in a hot kitchen is burning energy and wearing out its compressor — even if it's still holding temperature.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Ice Buildup on Evaporator</h3>
        <p>Defrost system failure — defrost heater, timer, or thermostat. The defrost cycle melts accumulated frost from the evaporator coils on a schedule. When the system fails, frost builds until airflow is blocked. The unit runs but can't circulate cold air effectively. Progressive temperature rise follows, usually over several days.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Door Gasket Failure</h3>
        <p>In a commercial kitchen with staff opening and closing the freezer door 40–60 times per shift, gaskets wear 3–5x faster than in lighter-use environments. A gasket that doesn't fully seal admits warm, humid kitchen air continuously — forcing the compressor to work harder and causing frost buildup near the door. We carry gaskets for True, Hoshizaki, and Turbo Air on the van.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Not Starting / Dead Unit</h3>
        <p>Failed start relay (a $30–$50 part that is the most common reason a compressor "fails"), overload protector tripped due to overheating from dirty condenser, or a wiring fault. We check the start relay and overload first before diagnosing compressor failure — many "dead compressors" are actually failed start relays that are a 20-minute repair.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="problem-card">
        <h3>Unusual Noises</h3>
        <p>Rattling or grinding from the evaporator fan motor (bearing failure — common on units in vibration-heavy kitchen environments), buzzing from a failing start relay before compressor failure, or hissing from a refrigerant leak. Early diagnosis of fan bearing failure prevents the evaporator ice-over that follows when the fan stops entirely.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- ENERGY BILL BLOCK -->
    <div class="energy-block">
      <div class="e-label">⚡ Hidden Early Warning Sign</div>
      <h3>A spike in electricity consumption often precedes a temperature failure by weeks</h3>
      <p>Commercial freezers in busy SoCal kitchens running next to ovens and fryers work in harsh ambient conditions — the effect is amplified in Inland Empire and Valley kitchens where outside ambient hits 100°F+ for weeks of the summer. When condenser coils accumulate grease and dust — which happens faster in commercial kitchens than almost any other environment — the compressor has to run longer and harder to reject heat into an already warm space. The result: energy consumption climbs 20–30% before the unit starts losing temperature. The unit appears to be working normally. The electricity bill tells a different story.</p>
      <p>If your utility bill increased and no new equipment was added, a service call to inspect and clean the condenser coils is almost always cost-justified. Condenser coil cleaning on a commercial reach-in freezer typically takes 30–45 minutes and costs far less than the repair bill that follows when the compressor fails from sustained overheating.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

