<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">07 — Recent Repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What our technicians actually fixed recently</h2>

    <div class="repairs-grid">
      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Koreatown · Korean BBQ Restaurant · True T-35F Reach-In</div>
        <h3>"Freezer reading 12°F this morning — all our marinated meats inside"</h3>
        <p>Failed start relay on a True T-35F single-door reach-in freezer — the compressor wasn't starting because the start relay, a small component that initiates compressor startup, had failed. The unit appeared completely dead: no compressor sound, fan running, no cooling. The restaurant had a full prep day's worth of marinated proteins inside and had called us in a panic assuming they needed a new compressor.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Diagnosed start relay failure by shaking the relay — a rattling sound confirmed the internal contact had failed. Replaced with OEM True start relay. Compressor started immediately on first cycle. Temperature pulled to 2°F within 90 minutes. All protein inventory was still crystallized at 12°F — fully recovered. Total repair cost: $165 including diagnostic. Customer's assumption that they needed a $900+ compressor replacement was wrong — start relay failure is the most commonly misdiagnosed compressor issue we see.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">East Hollywood · Thai Restaurant · Turbo Air TGF-49F Two-Door Reach-In</div>
        <h3>"Freezer running all day without shutting off — energy bill jumped"</h3>
        <p>Dirty condenser coils on a Turbo Air two-door reach-in that had been running next to a gas range in a hot kitchen for 14 months without a service visit. The condenser — located at the bottom front of the unit, directly in the path of kitchen heat — had accumulated a dense layer of grease and dust. The compressor was running continuously, unable to reject enough heat to cycle off. Temperature was holding at 2°F but the unit was consuming roughly 35% more electricity than normal.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Deep-cleaned condenser coils with commercial degreaser — removed significant grease buildup. Compressor began cycling normally within 20 minutes of cleaning. Monitored through 3 full compressor cycles to confirm proper on/off behavior. Checked door gaskets on both doors — center door gasket had compression fatigue on the bottom edge; replaced as part of the visit. Enrolled the restaurant in quarterly maintenance — kitchen proximity to gas ranges makes quarterly condenser cleaning the right interval for this installation.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Newport Beach (OC) · Coastal Seafood Restaurant · Beverage-Air HBF49 Two-Door</div>
        <h3>"Freezer holding 8°F — affecting our prep schedule for tonight's service"</h3>
        <p>Defrost system failure on a Beverage-Air HBF49 two-door reach-in at a Newport Beach seafood restaurant — the defrost timer had failed, leaving the defrost cycle stuck in "off" position for an estimated 10–14 days. Frost had accumulated 1.5–2 inches thick on the evaporator coil, completely blocking airflow. Temperature was holding at 8°F and climbing slowly as the unit struggled to circulate any cold air through the iced-over coil. Front-of-house service that night needed seafood pulled by 4pm and the manager called us at 11am.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Manual defrost of the iced evaporator coil using heat gun — 45 minutes to clear without damaging coil fins. Replaced failed Paragon defrost timer with OEM Beverage-Air part. Replaced defrost thermostat simultaneously — industry practice when heater fails as the thermostat is a consumable that degrades at similar rate. Verified three full defrost cycles before leaving. Temperature pulled to -2°F by 2:30pm — restaurant pulled seafood for service on time. Coastal humidity in Newport Beach makes defrost system health a higher-priority maintenance item than inland kitchens.</div>
      </div>

      <div class="repair-card">
        <div class="repair-title">Thousand Oaks (Ventura) · Catering Commissary · Hoshizaki F-1001MLJ Three-Door</div>
        <h3>"Slow refrigerant leak — temperature drifting up over two weeks"</h3>
        <p>Refrigerant leak at evaporator coil fitting on a Hoshizaki three-door reach-in used by a multi-event catering operation in Thousand Oaks. The slow leak had been reducing refrigerant charge over approximately 3 weeks, causing the unit to run longer each cycle but still maintain temperature — until it couldn't. By the time the lead chef noticed the drift, the unit was holding 8°F and declining. Catering bookings for the following weekend included two large weddings — they could not afford to lose the unit through Saturday service.</p>
        <div class="repair-detail">Located leak with electronic detector and UV dye at evaporator coil fitting. Repaired fitting, pressure-tested for 2 hours. Recharged with correct R-404A quantity per Hoshizaki spec. Temperature pulled to -2°F within 2 hours. Installed permanent UV dye for ongoing leak monitoring. Discussed a maintenance contract for the catering kitchen — high-event-density catering operations need more structured maintenance oversight than steady-state restaurants.</div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

