<!-- FAQ -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">09 — Frequently Asked Questions</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Commercial freezer repair — what SoCal operators ask us</h2>

    <div class="faq-list">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How much does commercial freezer repair cost?</h3>
        <p>Commercial diagnostic is $120, applied to the repair if approved. Most reach-in freezer repairs run $180–$550. Start relay, fan motor, door gasket, or defrost component is toward the lower end. Compressor or refrigerant work runs higher. Written estimate before any work begins.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Which areas of Southern California do you cover for commercial freezer repair?</h3>
        <p>Same-day across <strong>Los Angeles, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, and Riverside counties</strong> — Koreatown and East Hollywood restaurants, Newport Beach and Anaheim coastal kitchens, Thousand Oaks and Westlake Village suburban operators, Rancho Cucamonga and Riverside Inland Empire commissaries. Eight service territories total, dispatched from the closest tech to your kitchen. BHGS Licensed #A49573, EPA 608 + C-38 across the entire footprint.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>My commercial reach-in freezer is above 0°F — what should I do?</h3>
        <p>Move your highest-value frozen inventory to backup cold storage immediately. Document the temperature. Call us at {phone} — commercial freezer calls get same-day priority. Check the door gasket seal while you wait — a failing gasket is the most overlooked cause of gradual temperature rise in high-use commercial freezers.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>What's the difference between commercial reach-in and walk-in freezer repair?</h3>
        <p>Reach-in freezers are self-contained upright units — compressor built in. Walk-in freezers are room-sized systems with separate components including floor heaters, anti-sweat door heaters, and remote condensing units. Different failure modes, different repair approach. This page covers reach-in, undercounter, and chest freezers. For walk-in service, see our <a href="/commercial/walk-in-freezer-repair/" style="color:var(--red);">Walk-In Freezer Repair page</a>.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>My electricity bill spiked — could my commercial freezer be causing it?</h3>
        <p>Yes. A freezer working against dirty condenser coils, a failing door gasket, or low refrigerant consumes 20–30% more electricity before losing temperature. The effect is amplified in Inland Empire and Valley kitchens where summer ambient hits 100°F+. If your bill increased and no new equipment was added, a condenser coil cleaning service call is almost always cost-justified compared to the repair that follows when the compressor fails from sustained overheating.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>How often should a commercial reach-in freezer be serviced?</h3>
        <p>Every 3–4 months for freezers in busy restaurant kitchens next to cooking equipment — quarterly is the right interval for SoCal kitchens running through Inland Empire and Valley summer ambient stress. Every 6 months minimum for lower-traffic operations. Quarterly coil cleaning prevents the single most common commercial freezer failure mode across SoCal — compressor overheating from condenser fouling in hot kitchen environments.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Do you repair True, Hoshizaki, and Turbo Air commercial freezers?</h3>
        <p>Yes. True, Hoshizaki, Turbo Air, and Beverage-Air are our most common service calls across SoCal. True T-series parts carried on the van. All refrigerant work EPA 608 certified and C-38 licensed.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>Should I repair or replace my commercial reach-in freezer?</h3>
        <p>Commercial reach-in freezers last 10–15 years with proper maintenance. Under 8 years old, repair almost always makes sense. Over 12 years with compressor failure, we'll give you an honest assessment including estimated remaining life and replacement cost comparison. We'll tell you directly if replacing makes more financial sense.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <h3>When does it make sense to repair vs replace a commercial freezer?</h3>
        <p>Under 8 years old: repair, almost always. 8–12 years with a single component failure (start relay, fan motor, door gasket, defrost system): repair. 12+ years with compressor or sealed-system failure on a unit with deferred maintenance: we'll quote both repair and replacement and tell you directly which makes more financial sense. A new commercial reach-in freezer is $2,500–$6,000 plus install — repair is almost always the right call unless the unit has accumulated multiple end-of-life issues simultaneously.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

